    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "2.\nLabor unions in the US grew rapidly during the 19th and early 20th centuries, evolving their legal protection from the Fair Labor Standards Act of 1938 to the National Labor Relations Act of 1935.\nMembership peaked in 1954 with nearly 35% of the workforce, but since then, it has steadily declined due to shifts toward manufacturing and anti-union legislation in many sectors.\nToday, unions represent roughly 10–11% of private sector employees, making them a smaller but more influential voice focused on high-skill industries and public employees.\nWhile organizing drives remain competitive, the current climate presents both challenges regarding political opposition and opportunities for strong business unions to negotiate for worker rights.",
